{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/a-walkthru-for-writing-better-functions-6cb37f2fa58c", "time": 1683004766.489589, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/a-walkthru-for-writing-better-functions-6cb37f2fa58c/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "A walkthrough for writing better functions | by Dipam Vasani | Towards Data Science", "h1": "A walkthrough for writing better functions", "description": "I have seen that a lot of beginner programmers don\u2019t use functions while programming. And when I force them to write one, they just copy-paste a bunch of code into a function and call it done. The\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["I have seen that a lot of beginner programmers don\u2019t use functions while programming. And when I force them to write one, they just copy-paste a bunch of code into a function and call it done.", "The function will have no arguments, no flexibility for various data structures and no reusability. Variables will be declared inside the function. Numbers will be used in various places instead of variables. And there will be no type-checking, no tests to see if it can break. The list just goes on. The function will work for their particular assignment and that\u2019s it.", "In this article, I will try to walk you through one code example and thought process behind writing better functions. I hope that seeing this example and trying some of these ideas will give you an intuitive sense of how to write better functions for the future.", "Recently, I was working a Computer Vision assignment which required us to write Convolution from scratch. I will go through bits of that code.", "Tip #1: The first point to always remember when writing a function is to make them do one thing and just one thing.", "This tip will help you keep your functions short and simple. Don\u2019t put everything in it. Let\u2019s take a look at the function we wrote to read image files.", "We started with something like this:", "We read an image, convert it to greyscale, turn it into a numpy array and then return it. Now this is a neat function, but it\u2019s not flexible.", "Improvement #1: We don\u2019t always want greyscale images. Hence we include an argument for that. And that\u2019s our next tip.", "Tip #2: In our functions, we use libraries. The arguments that we pass to these libraries make good arguments for our function as well.", "And this is a really useful tip. Especially if you are using something like matplotlib and you are not aware of all the arguments a function takes, just include a **kwargs as an argument to your function and pass it along happily to matplotlib.", "Another thing we might want to change is the conversion to a numpy array. What if the user does not need a numpy array but just a PIL Image. Well, give him that option.", "Tip #3: Give the user a lot of choices to take the output of your function in many different directions.", "Our function is now quite flexible and can be reused in many other places. Even if not the same one, but with minor changes. Example, reusing it by changing default parameters. Which reminds me, we need to be smart about our defaults. In our current example, mode = None.", "However, like I mentioned before, we only need greyscale images for this one. Hence we should initialize it to \"L\" and not None. We don\u2019t want to do:", "However, we also don\u2019t want to do:", "Hence we can create another function as follows:", "See how nicely our function is building up. One more thing you can do is instead of passing the names of image files manually, retrieve them using code.", "Google how to get all image extensions. Google how to use the glob library to retrieve all files with certain extensions. And then code it yourself right now.", "Tip #4: Make your code work for multiple data structures", "The final tip is to include different behaviors for different data structures where applicable. The point is not to break the code and make it work for most things.", "That will be it for this article. I hope this walkthru helps you write better code in the future. You can see that now the read_image function can be used almost everywhere as compared to where we started. You will not start with the best functions. But keep refactoring your code and you will improve it a lot.", "One thing I would like to point out before I end though, is that, although you learnt all these tips, don\u2019t overdo them. Keep your functions minimalistic yet super useful.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F6cb37f2fa58c&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-walkthru-for-writing-better-functions-6cb37f2fa58c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-walkthru-for-writing-better-functions-6cb37f2fa58c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-walkthru-for-writing-better-functions-6cb